Subject: throttle EVDI pump grab_pixels per handle to 60Hz

The EVDI kernel has zero rate-limiting against the EDID refresh
(verified by reading evdi_painter.c / evdi_modeset.c on v1.14.16 —
pure event-driven, no period gate anywhere). Kwin's "vblank complete"
signal on a virtual connector IS our pump's grab_pixels ioctl
releasing painter->vblank via evdi_send_vblank() at
evdi_painter.c:1185. So the rate at which we ACK pageflips IS the
rate at which kwin schedules new commits.

With patch 0020's 500us pump iteration we ACK up to 2000 flips/sec.
Even with patch 0015's revised gamescope command line (no
--immediate-flips, `-o $(APOLLO_CLIENT_FPS)` cap), kwin's own
RenderLoop on Plasma 6 + RDNA3 can still commit faster than the
60Hz EDID under load — measured at ~90 events/s during real streams
([FPS-EVDI] events=90-95/s from patch 0020's instrumentation). The
encoder then drops ~38/s of the over-rate via the
`time_diff < -frame_variation_threshold` path in video.cpp, leaving
~53/s encoded — exactly the 49-58fps the Steam Deck reports.

This patch adds a per-handle "earliest next grab" timestamp tracked
in a std::map<evdi_handle, steady_clock::time_point>. Before each
poll on a handle's event fd we check the elapsed time; if it's
less than 16667us (= 1/60s) we skip both the poll syscall and the
grab_pixels ioctl for that iteration. Vblank stays queued in the
kernel; kwin's commit_state thread blocks on the pending-pageflip
check in drm_atomic_helper_setup_commit and won't schedule the
next commit until we ACK.

Net result: kwin paces itself to exactly 60Hz, the encoder's
variation-threshold path never fires for "too early" frames, and
the stream holds a clean 60fps end-to-end.

The cap is currently a compile-time constant (60Hz) because all
Apollo streaming targets in this project are 60fps. A future patch
can plumb the configured client FPS through to here if needed.

